<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-inverse-of-2-by-2-matrices-ii" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Inverse of 2 by 2 Matrices II</title>

    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <p>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        1.0 Numbers and Algebra
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        1.7 Matrices I
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title>
                    <p>
                        <ul>
                            <li>Determine the inverse of a 2 by 2 matrix</li>
                            <li>Solve linear equations in two unknowns using matrix method</li>
                        </ul>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p>
                        11
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p>
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Problem-Solving and Discovery</title>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Teaching Idea</title>
                <p>
                    This section uses a two-stage guided discovery. Learners first meet an inverse matrix and spot its pattern without being told the formula. They then derive that formula themselves by solving a system of simultaneous equations — first with specific numbers, then with general letters.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Materials Needed</title>
                <p>
                    One printed activity sheet per pair, pens or pencils, and board space for collecting learner findings.
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>

    <!-- ============================================================
         HOOK: Pattern recognition before instruction
    ============================================================ -->

    <activity xml:id="activity-hook-pattern">
        <title> What Do You Notice?</title>

        <statement>
            <p>
                Here are three matrices, each paired with a mystery matrix. In each case the two matrices have been multiplied together.
            </p>
            <p>
                With your partner: multiply each pair together and record what you get. Then look carefully at the mystery matrices. What patterns do you notice?
            </p>
            <ol marker="(a)">
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <me>
                            \begin{bmatrix} 3 \amp 2 \\ 1 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}
                            \times
                            \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp -2 \\ -1 \amp 3 \end{bmatrix}
                            = \mathord{?}
                        </me>
                    </p>
                    <solution component="lesson-plan">
                        <p>
                            <me>
                                \begin{bmatrix} 3(1)+2(-1) \amp 3(-2)+2(3) \\ 1(1)+1(-1) \amp 1(-2)+1(3) \end{bmatrix}
                                = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}.
                            </me>
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <me>
                            \begin{bmatrix} 4 \amp 1 \\ 3 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}
                            \times
                            \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp -1 \\ -3 \amp 4 \end{bmatrix}
                            = \mathord{?}
                        </me>
                    </p>
                    <solution component="lesson-plan">
                        <p>
                            <me>
                                \begin{bmatrix} 4(1)+1(-3) \amp 4(-1)+1(4) \\ 3(1)+1(-3) \amp 3(-1)+1(4) \end{bmatrix}
                                = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}.
                            </me>
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <me>
                            \begin{bmatrix} 2 \amp 5 \\ 1 \amp 3 \end{bmatrix}
                            \times
                            \begin{bmatrix} 3 \amp -5 \\ -1 \amp 2 \end{bmatrix}
                            = \mathord{?}
                        </me>
                    </p>
                    <solution component="lesson-plan">
                        <p>
                            <me>
                                \begin{bmatrix} 2(3)+5(-1) \amp 2(-5)+5(2) \\ 1(3)+3(-1) \amp 1(-5)+3(2) \end{bmatrix}
                                = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}.
                            </me>
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                </li>
            </ol>
            <p>
                After multiplying, look at the three mystery matrices alongside the original matrices. Discuss:
            </p>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>What happened to the diagonal entries?</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>What happened to the off-diagonal entries?</p>
                </li>
            </ul>
            <p>
                Write down your best guess for the rule in your own words. You will check whether your guess is right by the end of this section.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </activity>

    <!-- ============================================================
         NARRATIVE BRIDGE
    ============================================================ -->
    <!-- ============================================================
         PART 1: Concrete simultaneous equations
    ============================================================ -->

    <activity xml:id="activity-sim-equations-specific">
        <title>Part 1: Solving a Pair of Simultaneous Equations</title>

        <axiom component="lesson-plan">
            <title>Notes on Part 1</title>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Suggested Time</title>
                    <p>8 minutes</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Purpose</title>
                    <p>
                        Students solve a concrete system by elimination. This is revision — they have done this before. The point is to make the elimination steps explicit and visible, because those same steps will be repeated with letters in Part 3 to produce the inverse formula.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
        </axiom>

        <statement>
            <p>
                Consider the following pair of simultaneous equations:
                <md>
                    <mrow number="yes" xml:id="eq1"> 2x + y \amp= 5 </mrow>
                    <mrow number="yes" xml:id="eq2">  3x + 2y \amp= 8 </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <ol marker="(a)">
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Can you solve these equations for <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>?
                    </p>
                    <solution component="lesson-plan">
                        <p>
                            Multiply <xref ref="eq1"/> by 2:
                            <md>
                                <mrow number="yes" xml:id="eq1-double">4x + 2y \amp= 10</mrow>
                            </md>
                            Subtract <xref ref="eq2"/> from <xref ref="eq1-double"/>:
                            <md>
                                 <mrow> (4x+2y)-(3x+2y)\amp= 10-8</mrow>
                                 <mrow> x \amp= 2 </mrow>
                            </md>
                            To find <m>y</m>, substitute back into <xref ref="eq1"/>:
                            <md>
                                <mrow> 2(2) + y \amp= 5 </mrow>
                                <mrow>y \amp= 1 </mrow>
                            </md>.
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Verify your solution by checking that both original equations are satisfied.
                    </p>
                    <solution component="lesson-plan">
                        <p>
                            Checking <xref ref="eq1"/>: <md><mrow>2(2)+1=5\,\checkmark</mrow></md>
                            Checking <xref ref="eq2"/>: <md><mrow>3(2)+2(1)=8\,\checkmark</mrow></md>
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </statement>
    </activity>

    <!-- ============================================================
         PART 2: Rewrite as a matrix equation, notice the connection
    ============================================================ -->

    <activity xml:id="activity-matrix-form">
        <title>Part 2: Writing the System as a Matrix Equation</title>

        <statement>
            <p>
                The system from Part 1 can be written compactly using matrices. Define
                <me>
                    A = \begin{bmatrix} 2 \amp 1 \\ 3 \amp 2 \end{bmatrix}, \qquad
                    \mathbf{x} = \begin{bmatrix} x \\ y \end{bmatrix}, \qquad
                    \mathbf{b} = \begin{bmatrix} 5 \\ 8 \end{bmatrix}.
                </me>
            </p>
            <ol marker="(a)">
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Expand the matrix product <m>A\mathbf{x}</m>. Show that the equation <m>A\mathbf{x} = \mathbf{b}</m> is exactly the same as the two simultaneous equations in Part 1.
                    </p>
                    <solution component="lesson-plan">
                        <p>
                            <me>
                                A\mathbf{x} = \begin{bmatrix}2 \amp 1 \\ 3 \amp 2\end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix}x \\ y\end{bmatrix}
                                = \begin{bmatrix}2x+y \\ 3x+2y\end{bmatrix}.
                            </me>
                            Setting this equal to <m>\begin{bmatrix}5 \\ 8\end{bmatrix}</m> recovers equations and <xref ref="eq1"/>, <xref ref="eq2"/>
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        In ordinary arithmetic, if <m>a \cdot x = b</m>, we solve by writing <m>x = \frac{b}{a} = a^{-1} \cdot b</m>. By analogy, if <m>A\mathbf{x} = \mathbf{b}</m> and we knew a matrix <m>A^{-1}</m> that <q>undoes</q> <m>A</m>, how would you write the solution for <m>\mathbf{x}</m>?
                    </p>
                    <solution component="lesson-plan">
                        <p>
                            Left-multiply both sides by <m>A^{-1}</m>:
                            <me>A^{-1}A\mathbf{x} = A^{-1}\mathbf{b} \implies I\mathbf{x} = A^{-1}\mathbf{b} \implies \mathbf{x} = A^{-1}\mathbf{b}.</me>
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        From Part 1 you found <m>x = 2</m> and <m>y = 1</m>.
                        The inverse of <m>A</m> turns out to be
                        <me>A^{-1} = \begin{bmatrix}2 \amp -1 \\ -3 \amp 2\end{bmatrix}.</me>
                        Compute <m>A^{-1}\mathbf{b}</m> and confirm that you get the same answer as Part 1.
                    </p>
                    <solution component="lesson-plan">
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow>
                                    A^{-1}\mathbf{b}
                                    \amp= \begin{bmatrix}2 \amp -1 \\ -3 \amp 2\end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix}5 \\ 8\end{bmatrix}
                                </mrow>
                                <mrow>
                                    \amp= \begin{bmatrix}2(5)+(-1)(8) \\ (-3)(5)+2(8)\end{bmatrix}
                                </mrow>
                                <mrow>
                                    \amp= \begin{bmatrix}2 \\ 1\end{bmatrix}. \checkmark
                                </mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </statement>
    </activity>

    <!-- ============================================================
         PART 3: General case — derive the formula
    ============================================================ -->

    <activity xml:id="activity-general-derivation">
        <title>Part 3: The General Case — Deriving the Formula</title>

        <axiom component="lesson-plan">
            <title>Notes on Part 3</title>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Suggested Time</title>
                    <p>10 minutes</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Purpose</title>
                    <p>
                        Students repeat the elimination from Part 1 with general coefficients <m>a, b, c, d</m> and general right-hand sides <m>w, z</m>. Each elimination step produces one entry of <m>A^{-1}</m>. The formula is not given — it emerges from their own algebra. Encourage pairs to compare each step with what they did in Part 1.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
        </axiom>

        <statement>
            <p>
                Now generalise. Replace the specific numbers with letters:
                <md>
                    <mrow number="yes" xml:id="eq3"> ax + by \amp= 5 </mrow>
                    <mrow number="yes" xml:id="eq4"> cx + dy \amp= 8 </mrow>
                </md>
                Here <m>a, b, c, d</m> are the coefficients. We want to solve for <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> in terms of these letters.
            </p>
            <p>
                Note that equations <xref ref="eq3"/> and <xref ref="eq4"/> are equivalent to the matrix equation:
                <md>
                    \begin{bmatrix}a \amp b \\ c \amp d \end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix}x \\ y\end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 5 \\ 8 \end{bmatrix}
                </md>
            </p>
            <ol marker="(a)">
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Eliminate <m>x</m> to get an equation in just <m>y</m>.
                    </p>
                    <solution component="lesson-plan">
                        <p>
                            Multiply <xref ref="eq3"/> by <m>c</m>: 
                            <md>
                                <mrow number="yes" xml:id="eq3c"> acx + bcy = 5c </mrow>
                            </md>
                            Multiply <xref ref="eq4"/> by <m>a</m>:
                            <md>
                                <mrow number="yes" xml:id="eq4a">acx + ady = 8a</mrow>
                            </md>
                            Subtract <xref ref="eq3c"/> from <xref ref="eq4a"/>:
                            <md>
                                <mrow>(acx + ady) - (acx + bcy) \amp = 8a - 5c </mrow>
                                <mrow>(ad - bc)y \amp= 8a - 5c</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Assuming <m>ad - bc \neq 0</m>, solve for <m>y</m>.
                    </p>
                    <solution component="lesson-plan">
                        <p>
                            <md>y = \frac{8a - 5c}{ad - bc}</md>
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Now solve for <m>x</m>.
                    </p>
                    <solution component="lesson-plan">
                        <p>
                            Inserting the value of <m>y</m> into <xref ref="eq3"/>:
                            <md>
                                <mrow>ax + b\left(\frac{8a - 5c}{ad - bc}\right) \amp= 5 </mrow>
                                <mrow>ax \amp= 5 - \frac{8ab - 5bc)}{ad - bc} </mrow>
                                <mrow>ax \amp= \frac{5ad - \cancel{5bc} - (8ab + \cancel{5bc})}{ad - bc} </mrow>
                                <mrow>ax \amp= \frac{5ad - 8ab}{ad - bc} </mrow>
                                <mrow>x \amp= \frac{5d - 8b}{ad - bc} </mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Write your solutions for <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> together as a single column vector. For simplicity, let <m>ad - bc = D</m>.
                    </p>
                    <solution component="lesson-plan">
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow> \begin{bmatrix}x \\ y\end{bmatrix} \amp= \begin{bmatrix}\dfrac{5d - 8b}{ad-bc} \\[6pt] \dfrac{8a - 5c}{ad-bc}\end{bmatrix} </mrow>
                                <mrow number="yes" xml:id="eq5"> \amp= \frac{1}{D}\begin{bmatrix}5d - 8b \\ 8a - 5c\end{bmatrix} </mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        You should get an expression involving the vector <m>\begin{bmatrix}5d - 8b \\ 8a - 5c\end{bmatrix}</m>. Try to rewrite this vector as a matrix multiplied by <m>\begin{bmatrix}5 \\ 8\end{bmatrix}</m> and thus write your solution for <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> as a matrix-vector product.
                    </p>
                    <solution component="lesson-plan">
                        <p> We have <m>\begin{bmatrix}5d - 8b \\ 8a - 5c\end{bmatrix}
                                = \begin{bmatrix}d \amp -b \\ -c \amp a\end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix}5 \\ 8\end{bmatrix}</m>, thus return to <xref ref="eq5"/>:
                            <md>
                                <mrow> \begin{bmatrix}x \\ y\end{bmatrix}
                                = \frac{1}{D}\begin{bmatrix}d \amp -b \\ -c \amp a\end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix}5 \\ 8\end{bmatrix} </mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Recall from Part 2 that the solution is also equal to <m>A^{-1}\mathbf{b}</m>, where <m>A = \begin{bmatrix}a \amp b \\ c \amp d\end{bmatrix}</m> and <m>\mathbf{b} = \begin{bmatrix}5 \\ 8\end{bmatrix}</m>. By comparing with your previoous answer, write down the formula for <m>A^{-1}</m>.
                    </p>
                    <solution component="lesson-plan">
                        <p>
                            Since <m>\mathbf{x} = A^{-1}\mathbf{b}</m>, the matrix multiplying <m>\begin{bmatrix}5 \\ 8\end{bmatrix}</m> in the previous question must be <m>A^{-1}</m>:
                            <me>
                                A^{-1} = \frac{1}{ad-bc}\begin{bmatrix}d \amp -b \\ -c \amp a\end{bmatrix}.
                            </me>
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </statement>
    </activity>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Whole-Class Consolidation</title>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>7 minutes</p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p>
                    Ask two or three pairs to share what they found. Then write the formula inverse formula.
                    Ask, <q>Where did this come from? Which step in your algebra gave you this?</q>
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Key Questions</title>
                <p>
                    Ask, <q>What happens if <m>ad - bc</m> equals zero? What would that mean in your system of equations?</q> Let learners suggest ideas such as no unique solution or parallel equations, then connect this to the idea of a non-invertible matrix.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Mnemonic</title>
                <p>
                    Introduce <em>Swap, Negate, Divide</em> only after the derivation: swap the diagonal entries, negate the off-diagonal entries, and divide by <m>ad-bc</m>.
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>


    <insight>
        <p>
            The formula for the inverse of the 2 by 2 matrix <m>A = \begin{bmatrix}a \amp b \\ c \amp d\end{bmatrix}</m> is:
            <md>
                A^{-1} = \frac{1}{ad-bc}\begin{bmatrix}d \amp -b \\ -c \amp a \end{bmatrix}
            </md>
            This only exists if <m>ad - bc \neq 0</m>.<fn>In <xref ref="sec-determinant"/> we will see that <m>ad - bc</m> is the <term>determinant</term> of the matrix.</fn>
        </p>
        <p>
            You can remember this formula by the mnemonic <em>Swap, Negate, Divide</em>: 
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Swap</title>
                    <p>
                        Swap the positions of the diagonal entries <m>a</m> and <m>d</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Negate</title>
                    <p>
                        Negate the off-diagonal entries <m>b</m> and <m>c</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Divide</title>
                    <p>
                        Divide each entry by <m>ad-bc</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
    </insight>

    <!-- ============================================================
         EXAMPLES
    ============================================================ -->

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/example-intro.ptx" />

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Your friend used a matrix to encode a secret message. She multiplied a vector of numbers by the matrix
                <me>M=\begin{bmatrix}3 \amp 1 \\ 5 \amp 2\end{bmatrix}</me>
                to scramble it. After encoding, she got the message vector <m>\begin{bmatrix}11 \\ 19\end{bmatrix}</m>.
            </p>
            <ol marker="(a)">
                <li>
                    <p>Find <m>M^{-1}</m> using the formula.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Use <m>M^{-1}</m> to decode the message by computing <m>M^{-1}\begin{bmatrix}11 \\ 19\end{bmatrix}</m>.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>What was the original vector?</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Could she have chosen any encoding matrix? What would go wrong if she chose <m>\begin{bmatrix}2 \amp 4 \\ 1 \amp 2\end{bmatrix}</m>?</p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <ol marker="(a)">
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>ad - bc = 3(2) - 1(5) = 1</m>, so
                        <me>M^{-1}=\frac{1}{1}\begin{bmatrix}2 \amp -1 \\ -5 \amp 3\end{bmatrix}=\begin{bmatrix}2 \amp -1 \\ -5 \amp 3\end{bmatrix}.</me>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <me>
                            M^{-1}\begin{bmatrix}11 \\ 19\end{bmatrix}
                            =\begin{bmatrix}2 \amp -1 \\ -5 \amp 3\end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix}11 \\ 19\end{bmatrix}
                            =\begin{bmatrix}22-19 \\ -55+57\end{bmatrix}
                            =\begin{bmatrix}3 \\ 2\end{bmatrix}.
                        </me>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>The original vector was <m>\begin{bmatrix}3 \\ 2\end{bmatrix}</m>.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        No. The proposed matrix has <m>ad - bc = 2(2)-4(1)=0</m>, so it has no inverse. If there is no inverse, the encoded message cannot be decoded.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>Let <m>A = \begin{bmatrix} 2 \amp 1 \\ 3 \amp 2 \end{bmatrix}</m> and <m>\mathbf{b} = \begin{bmatrix} 7 \\ 12 \end{bmatrix}</m>.</p>
            <ol marker="(a)">
                <li>
                    <p>Find <m>A^{-1}</m>.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>If <m>\mathbf{x} = \begin{bmatrix}x \\ y\end{bmatrix}</m>, solve <m>A\mathbf{x} = \mathbf{b}</m> using the inverse.</p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <ol marker="(a)">
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Applying the formula,
                        <md>
                            <mrow> A^{-1}
                            \amp = \frac{1}{(2)(2) - (1)(3)} \begin{bmatrix} 2 \amp -1 \\ -3 \amp 2 \end{bmatrix} </mrow>
                            <mrow> \amp = \begin{bmatrix} 2 \amp -1 \\ -3 \amp 2 \end{bmatrix}. </mrow>
                        </md>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Since <m>A\mathbf{x} = \mathbf{b}</m>, left-multiply both sides by <m>A^{-1}</m> to get <m>\mathbf{x} = A^{-1}\mathbf{b}</m>:
                        <md>
                            <mrow> \mathbf{x} \amp = \begin{bmatrix} 2 \amp -1 \\ -3 \amp 2 \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} 7 \\ 12 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ 3 \end{bmatrix}. </mrow>
                        </md>
                        Hence <m>x = 2</m> and <m>y = 3</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>Solve the system <m>2x - y = 1</m> and <m>3x + 2y = 14</m> using the inverse method.</p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Write the system in matrix form:
                <me>\begin{bmatrix} 2 \amp -1 \\ 3 \amp 2 \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} x \\ y \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 14 \end{bmatrix}.</me>
                <m>ad - bc = 2(2)-(-1)(3)=7</m>, so the inverse is
                <me>A^{-1} = \frac{1}{7} \begin{bmatrix} 2 \amp 1 \\ -3 \amp 2 \end{bmatrix}.</me>
                Therefore,
                <md>
                    <mrow> \begin{bmatrix} x \\ y \end{bmatrix} = A^{-1} \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 14 \end{bmatrix} = \frac{1}{7}\begin{bmatrix} 2(1)+1(14) \\ -3(1)+2(14) \end{bmatrix} = \frac{1}{7}\begin{bmatrix}16 \\ 25\end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix}2 \\ 4\end{bmatrix}. </mrow>
                </md>
                So <m>x = 2</m> and <m>y = 4</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                A community theatre in Kisumu sells adult and student tickets. Two student tickets and three adult tickets cost KSh <m>1800</m>. Five student tickets and two adult tickets cost KSh <m>2300</m>.
            </p>
            <ol marker="(a)">
                <li>
                    <p>Let <m>x</m> be the cost of one student ticket and <m>y</m> be the cost of one adult ticket. Write the system of equations.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Write the system in matrix form and find the inverse of the coefficient matrix.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Use the inverse to solve for <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>.</p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <ol marker="(a)">
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <md>
                            <mrow> 2x + 3y \amp= 1800 </mrow>
                            <mrow> 5x + 2y \amp= 2300 </mrow>
                        </md>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        In matrix form:
                        <me>\begin{bmatrix} 2 \amp 3 \\ 5 \amp 2 \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} x \\ y \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 1800 \\ 2300 \end{bmatrix}.</me>
                        <m>ad-bc = 2(2)-3(5)=-11</m>, so
                        <md>
                            <mrow> A^{-1} \amp = \frac{1}{-11} \begin{bmatrix} 2 \amp -3 \\ -5 \amp 2 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} -\tfrac{2}{11} \amp \tfrac{3}{11} \\ \tfrac{5}{11} \amp -\tfrac{2}{11} \end{bmatrix}. </mrow>
                        </md>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <md>
                            <mrow> \begin{bmatrix} x \\ y \end{bmatrix} \amp = A^{-1} \begin{bmatrix} 1800 \\ 2300 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} -\tfrac{2}{11} \amp \tfrac{3}{11} \\ \tfrac{5}{11} \amp -\tfrac{2}{11} \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} 1800 \\ 2300 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 300 \\ 400 \end{bmatrix}. </mrow>
                        </md>
                        So a student ticket costs KSh <m>300</m> and an adult ticket costs KSh <m>400</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <!-- ============================================================
         EXERCISES (carried over unchanged from the original file)
    ============================================================ -->

    <exercises>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>Find the inverse of <m>M = \begin{bmatrix} -1 \amp 4 \\ 2 \amp 5 \end{bmatrix}</m>.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow> M^{-1}
                        \amp = \frac{1}{(-1)(5) - (4)(2)} \begin{bmatrix} 5 \amp -4 \\ -2 \amp -1 \end{bmatrix} </mrow>
                        <mrow> \amp = -\frac{1}{13} \begin{bmatrix} 5 \amp -4 \\ -2 \amp -1 \end{bmatrix} </mrow>
                        <mrow> \amp = \begin{bmatrix} -\tfrac{5}{13} \amp \tfrac{4}{13} \\ \tfrac{2}{13} \amp \tfrac{1}{13} \end{bmatrix}. </mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>Find the inverse of each matrix, if it exists.</p>
                <ol marker="(a)" cols="2">
                    <li><p><m>A = \begin{bmatrix} 2 \amp 1 \\ 5 \amp 3 \end{bmatrix}</m></p></li>
                    <li><p><m>B = \begin{bmatrix} 4 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp -2 \end{bmatrix}</m></p></li>
                    <li><p><m>C = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 2 \\ 2 \amp 4 \end{bmatrix}</m></p></li>
                    <li><p><m>D = \begin{bmatrix} -3 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 5 \end{bmatrix}</m></p></li>
                    <li><p><m>E = \begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp 1 \\ -1 \amp 2 \end{bmatrix}</m></p></li>
                    <li><p><m>F = \begin{bmatrix} -2 \amp 3 \\ 1 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}</m></p></li>
                </ol>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <ol marker="(a)" cols="2">
                    <li><p><m>A^{-1} = \begin{bmatrix} 3 \amp -1 \\ -5 \amp 2 \end{bmatrix}</m></p></li>
                    <li><p><m>B^{-1} = \begin{bmatrix} \tfrac{1}{4} \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp -\tfrac{1}{2} \end{bmatrix}</m></p></li>
                    <li><p>No inverse, since <m>ad - bc = 1(4) - 2(2) = 0</m>.</p></li>
                    <li><p><m>D^{-1} = \begin{bmatrix} -\tfrac{1}{3} \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp \tfrac{1}{5} \end{bmatrix}</m></p></li>
                    <li><p><m>E^{-1} = \begin{bmatrix} 2 \amp -1 \\ 1 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}</m></p></li>
                    <li><p><m>F^{-1} = \begin{bmatrix} -\tfrac{1}{5} \amp \tfrac{3}{5} \\ \tfrac{1}{5} \amp \tfrac{2}{5} \end{bmatrix}</m></p></li>
                </ol>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>Find the inverse of each matrix, if it exists.</p>
                <ol marker="(a)" cols="2">
                    <li><p><m>A = \begin{bmatrix} 7 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 3 \end{bmatrix}</m></p></li>
                    <li><p><m>B = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp -4 \\ 2 \amp 5 \end{bmatrix}</m></p></li>
                    <li><p><m>C = \begin{bmatrix} -4 \amp -1 \\ 2 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}</m></p></li>
                    <li><p><m>D = \begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp -2 \\ 5 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}</m></p></li>
                    <li><p><m>E = \begin{bmatrix} -1 \amp 2 \\ 3 \amp -6 \end{bmatrix}</m></p></li>
                    <li><p><m>F = \begin{bmatrix} 2 \amp -3 \\ 1 \amp 4 \end{bmatrix}</m></p></li>
                </ol>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <ol marker="(a)" cols="2">
                    <li><p><m>A^{-1} = \begin{bmatrix} \tfrac{1}{7} \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp \tfrac{1}{3} \end{bmatrix}</m></p></li>
                    <li><p><m>B^{-1} = \begin{bmatrix} \tfrac{5}{13} \amp \tfrac{4}{13} \\ -\tfrac{2}{13} \amp \tfrac{1}{13} \end{bmatrix}</m></p></li>
                    <li><p><m>C^{-1} = \begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp \tfrac{1}{2} \\ -1 \amp -2 \end{bmatrix}</m></p></li>
                    <li><p><m>D^{-1} = \begin{bmatrix} \tfrac{1}{10} \amp \tfrac{1}{5} \\ -\tfrac{1}{2} \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}</m></p></li>
                    <li><p>No inverse, since <m>ad - bc = -1(-6) - 2(3) = 0</m>.</p></li>
                    <li><p><m>F^{-1} = \begin{bmatrix} \tfrac{4}{11} \amp \tfrac{3}{11} \\ -\tfrac{1}{11} \amp \tfrac{2}{11} \end{bmatrix}</m></p></li>
                </ol>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A printing kiosk in Nairobi charges for black-and-white pages and colour pages. A student prints 3 black-and-white pages and 2 colour pages for KSh <m>110</m>. Another student prints 5 black-and-white pages and 1 colour page for KSh <m>125</m>.
                </p>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li><p>Let <m>x</m> be the cost of one black-and-white page and <m>y</m> the cost of one colour page. Write the system of equations.</p></li>
                    <li><p>Write the system in matrix form and find the inverse of the coefficient matrix.</p></li>
                    <li><p>Use the inverse to solve for <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>.</p></li>
                </ol>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow>3x + 2y \amp= 110</mrow>
                                <mrow>5x + y \amp= 125</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            In matrix form:
                            <me>\begin{bmatrix} 3 \amp 2 \\ 5 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} x \\ y \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 110 \\ 125 \end{bmatrix}.</me>
                            <m>ad - bc = 3(1)-2(5)=-7</m>, so
                            <md>
                                <mrow> A^{-1} \amp = -\frac{1}{7} \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp -2 \\ -5 \amp 3 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} -\tfrac{1}{7} \amp \tfrac{2}{7} \\ \tfrac{5}{7} \amp -\tfrac{3}{7} \end{bmatrix}. </mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow> \begin{bmatrix} x \\ y \end{bmatrix} \amp = A^{-1} \begin{bmatrix} 110 \\ 125 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 20 \\ 25 \end{bmatrix}. </mrow>
                            </md>
                            So a black-and-white page costs KSh <m>20</m> and a colour page costs KSh <m>25</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A school bookshop sells notebooks and pens. Two notebooks and three pens cost KSh <m>480</m>, while five notebooks and one pen cost KSh <m>680</m>. Find the cost of one notebook and one pen using the matrix inverse method.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    The system is
                    <md>
                        <mrow>2x + 3y \amp= 480</mrow>
                        <mrow>5x + y \amp= 680</mrow>
                    </md>
                    so
                    <me>\begin{bmatrix} 2 \amp 3 \\ 5 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} x \\ y \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 480 \\ 680 \end{bmatrix}.</me>
                    <m>ad - bc = 2(1)-3(5)=-13</m>, so
                    <me>A^{-1} = -\frac{1}{13} \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp -3 \\ -5 \amp 2 \end{bmatrix}.</me>
                    Hence
                        <me>\begin{bmatrix} x \\ y \end{bmatrix} = A^{-1} \begin{bmatrix} 480 \\ 680 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 120 \\ 80 \end{bmatrix}.</me>
                        So a notebook costs KSh <m>120</m> and a pen costs KSh <m>80</m>.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A museum in Nairobi sells tourist and local tickets. Three tourist tickets and four local tickets cost KSh <m>2300</m>, while two tourist tickets and five local tickets cost KSh <m>2000</m>. Use the inverse method to find the cost of each ticket type.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    The system is
                    <md>
                        <mrow>3x + 4y \amp= 2300</mrow>
                        <mrow>2x + 5y \amp= 2000</mrow>
                    </md>
                    so
                    <me>\begin{bmatrix} 3 \amp 4 \\ 2 \amp 5 \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} x \\ y \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 2300 \\ 2000 \end{bmatrix}.</me>
                    <m>ad - bc = 3(5)-4(2)=7</m>, so
                    <me>A^{-1} = \frac{1}{7} \begin{bmatrix} 5 \amp -4 \\ -2 \amp 3 \end{bmatrix}.</me>
                    Therefore,
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\begin{bmatrix} x \\ y \end{bmatrix} \amp= \frac{1}{7}\begin{bmatrix}5 \amp -4 \\ -2 \amp 3\end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix}2300 \\ 2000\end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix}500 \\ 200\end{bmatrix}.</mrow>
                    </md>
                    So a tourist ticket costs KSh <m>500</m> and a local ticket costs KSh <m>200</m>.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <title>Inverse of the Product of Matrices</title>
            <statement>
                <p>Let <m>A = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 2 \\ 3 \amp 4 \end{bmatrix}</m> and <m>B = \begin{bmatrix} 2 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp 3 \end{bmatrix}</m>.</p>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li><p>Find <m>A^{-1}</m> and <m>B^{-1}</m>.</p></li>
                    <li><p>Compute <m>AB</m> and <m>(AB)^{-1}</m>.</p></li>
                    <li><p>Find <m>A^{-1}B^{-1}</m>. Is it equal to <m>(AB)^{-1}</m>?</p></li>
                    <li><p>Find <m>B^{-1}A^{-1}</m>. Is it equal to <m>(AB)^{-1}</m>?</p></li>
                    <li><p>If <m>C</m> is any invertible <m>2\times2</m> matrix, write a guess for <m>(ABC)^{-1}</m>.</p></li>
                </ol>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow>A^{-1} \amp= \frac{1}{4-6}\begin{bmatrix}4 \amp -2 \\ -3 \amp 1\end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix}-2 \amp 1 \\ \tfrac{3}{2} \amp -\tfrac{1}{2}\end{bmatrix},</mrow>
                                <mrow>B^{-1} \amp= \frac{1}{6}\begin{bmatrix}3 \amp -1 \\ 0 \amp 2\end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix}\tfrac{1}{2} \amp -\tfrac{1}{6} \\ 0 \amp \tfrac{1}{3}\end{bmatrix}.</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow>AB \amp= \begin{bmatrix}2 \amp 7 \\ 6 \amp 15\end{bmatrix},</mrow>
                                <mrow>(AB)^{-1} \amp= \frac{1}{30-42}\begin{bmatrix}15 \amp -7 \\ -6 \amp 2\end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix}-\tfrac{5}{4} \amp \tfrac{7}{12} \\ \tfrac{1}{2} \amp -\tfrac{1}{6}\end{bmatrix}.</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <me>A^{-1}B^{-1} = \begin{bmatrix}-1 \amp \tfrac{2}{3} \\ \tfrac{3}{4} \amp -\tfrac{5}{12}\end{bmatrix} \neq (AB)^{-1}.</me>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <me>B^{-1}A^{-1} = \begin{bmatrix}-\tfrac{5}{4} \amp \tfrac{7}{12} \\ \tfrac{1}{2} \amp -\tfrac{1}{6}\end{bmatrix} = (AB)^{-1}. \checkmark</me>
                        </p>
                        <note>
                            <p>
                                Why is the order reversed? Suppose <m>B</m> represents putting on socks and <m>A</m> represents putting on shoes. Then <m>AB</m> means socks first, then shoes. To undo this, we remove the shoes <m>(A^{-1})</m> first, then remove the socks <m>(B^{-1})</m>, giving <m>B^{-1}A^{-1}</m>.
                            </p>
                        </note>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p><me>(ABC)^{-1} = C^{-1}B^{-1}A^{-1}.</me></p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <title>Inverse of Diagonal Matrices</title>
            <statement>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>Let <m>M = \begin{bmatrix}5 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp -2\end{bmatrix}</m>. Find <m>M^{-1}</m>.</p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Let <m>N = \begin{bmatrix}a \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp b\end{bmatrix}</m>. Prove that
                            <me>N^{-1} = \begin{bmatrix}\tfrac{1}{a} \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp \tfrac{1}{b}\end{bmatrix}.</me>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow>M^{-1} \amp= \frac{1}{(5)(-2)-0}\begin{bmatrix}-2 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 5\end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix}\tfrac{1}{5} \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp -\tfrac{1}{2}\end{bmatrix}.</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow>N^{-1} \amp= \frac{1}{ab}\begin{bmatrix}b \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp a\end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix}\tfrac{1}{a} \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp \tfrac{1}{b}\end{bmatrix}.</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </solution>
        </exercise>
    </exercises>

